A very practical launch plan
Phase 1: newsletter proof of concept
Start with 8–10 issues.
Do not wait for perfection.
Each week:
shortlist 5 hooks,
choose 1 winner,
publish 1 teardown + rebuild.
Goal:
learn which type wins:
product launches,
viral demos,
GitHub repos,
Show HN tools,
AI research demos.
Phase 2: identify the strongest repeatable formats
Track:
open rate,
click rate,
read depth,
replies,
shares,
which hook categories convert best.
Phase 3: turn winners into YouTube
Only adapt the strongest issues.
Do not port every newsletter 1:1.
Phase 4: build a community loop
Ask audience to submit:
products to dissect,
repos to rebuild,
demos to test,
blind comparisons.
Now the audience feeds the engine.
The exact content buckets I’d use
You need recurring pillars.
Pillar 1: Viral rebuild
A hot launch or demo, rebuilt.
Pillar 2: Hype audit
A trending AI product tested for real depth.
Pillar 3: Feature extraction
Take one killer feature from a breakout product and show how to recreate only that.
Pillar 4: Better version
Rebuild the idea, but fix one weakness.
Pillar 5: Open-source equivalent
Take a polished commercial idea and build a lean open version.
That gives you freshness without losing brand consistency.
How YouTube should use retention data
YouTube’s own guidance is useful here:
the intro metric looks at how many viewers are still watching after the first 30 seconds,
spikes often mean rewatch/share-worthy moments,
dips mean abandonment or skipping,
and title/thumbnail should match what the opening actually delivers. (Google Help)
For Shorts, YouTube also explicitly advises thinking about how the first 1–2 seconds grab scrollers, and for longer videos it stresses that titles and thumbnails should accurately reflect the content. (YouTube)
So for your format:
first 5–15 seconds: state mission + show original product + show your attempt preview,
mid-video: create spike-worthy reveals,
every video: audit where viewers dipped and rewrite that section format.
YouTube’s creator guidance also emphasizes engineering story for retention, with a hook, a clear conflict, a build toward climax, and a reliable cadence. (blog.youtube)
That maps perfectly to your format.
One sharp editorial principle
Every issue/video should answer these 4 questions:
Why did this spread?
How does it probably work?
Can we rebuild the core?
What should builders learn from this?
If a candidate does not create strong answers for all four, skip it.
My honest view on the opportunity
This can absolutely work.
But only if you resist becoming:
generic AI news,
generic build-in-public,
generic tutorials,
generic “I cloned X.”
The winning version is:
high-signal hook + strong reverse engineering + visible build challenge + creator-grade storytelling + useful takeaway
That is rare.
You are essentially inventing:
MythBusters for AI products, with builder education hidden inside the entertainment.
That is a real format.

1) Hook scoring mechanism
Use this before committing to any newsletter issue or video.
Score each candidate from 1 to 5 on each dimension.
A. Attention strength
Question: Will a smart internet-native person care instantly?
Score guide:
1 = obscure, no existing signal
2 = mildly interesting niche launch
3 = decent momentum in one community
4 = clearly trending in a visible place
5 = breakout object with obvious curiosity
Examples of high scorers:
#1 Product Hunt launch
GitHub repo exploding in stars
viral X demo
Show HN thread with heavy engagement
B. Rebuildability
Question: Can we recreate the core experience fast enough for content?
Score guide:
1 = too complex, too infra-heavy
2 = possible but not practical for your format
3 = hard but can replicate a stripped-down version
4 = feasible with clear scoping
5 = ideal for a fast reverse-engineer/build challenge
C. Teachability
Question: Will rebuilding this naturally teach something valuable?
Score guide:
1 = cool, but little transferable learning
2 = mostly spectacle
3 = one good lesson
4 = several reusable lessons
5 = deeply instructive while still entertaining
D. Visual payoff
Question: Will the audience see obvious progress and a satisfying end result?
Score guide:
1 = mostly backend or invisible logic
2 = difficult to show on screen
3 = somewhat demo-able
4 = visibly satisfying
5 = highly screen-friendly and thumbnail-friendly
E. Reveal potential
Question: Is there likely to be a surprising insight?
Examples:
“The wow factor was mostly UX.”
“The hard part wasn’t the AI.”
“This looked magical but was mostly orchestration.”
“The original moat is not where people think.”
Score guide:
1 = no real insight beyond “we built it”
3 = one decent reveal
5 = multiple non-obvious takeaways
F. Originality safety
Question: Can you cover this without feeling like a lazy clone?
Score guide:
1 = feels derivative / uncomfortable
2 = hard to differentiate
3 = possible with careful framing
4 = clearly transformative
5 = easy to make original by focusing on mechanism, lessons, or improvement
G. Audience fit
Question: Does this fit your audience’s identity?
Your likely audience:
builders
AI-curious professionals
aspiring technical creators
founders / operators / developers
Score guide:
1 = interesting, but wrong audience
3 = somewhat relevant
5 = perfect overlap
H. Format elasticity
Question: Can this become multiple content assets?
Can it become:
newsletter issue
long-form video
short clip
tweet thread / LinkedIn post
repo / template
community challenge
Score guide:
1 = one-off
3 = two formats
5 = content flywheel material
Final hook score
Use this weighted formula:
Hook Score =
Attention strength × 2
Rebuildability × 2
Teachability × 2
Visual payoff × 1.5
Reveal potential × 1.5
Originality safety × 1
Audience fit × 1.5
Format elasticity × 1
Max score = 62.5
Decision rule
50+ = must cover
42–49 = strong candidate
34–41 = cover only if timing is right
below 34 = reject
Fast filter version
Before full scoring, ask 3 yes/no questions:
Would someone click this in under 3 seconds?
Can we rebuild the core in 1–2 focused sessions?
Will the audience learn something reusable?
If the answer is not “yes” to all three, skip.

2) Content pillars
You need recurring pillars so the channel feels like a show, not random experiments.
Pillar 1: Viral Rebuild
Format: A trending launch/demo/repo becomes a rebuild challenge.
Core question:
Can we recreate the core experience ourselves?
Works best for:
Product Hunt launches
GitHub repos
X demos
Show HN products
Why this matters:
This is your flagship format. It creates the strongest hook + story + payoff.
Example titles:
We Rebuilt Today’s #1 Product Hunt Launch
This AI Demo Went Viral. We Tried to Recreate It
We Reverse Engineered a Trending GitHub AI Tool
Pillar 2: Hype Audit
Format: Take a hyped product and test what’s real versus packaging.
Core question:
Is this actually impressive, or just smart presentation?
Why this matters:
This builds trust and gives you an opinion moat.
Example titles:
Is This Viral AI Product Actually Hard to Build?
We Tested the Hype Behind This Trending AI Tool
Pillar 3: Feature Extraction
Format: Don’t rebuild the whole product. Rebuild only the killer feature.
Core question:
What is the smallest piece that made this product spread?
Why this matters:
This is often more educational and more repeatable than full rebuilds.
Example titles:
We Rebuilt the One Feature That Made This App Blow Up
The Real Magic of This AI Product Was Just One Workflow
Pillar 4: Better Than the Original
Format: Rebuild the core idea, then improve one important thing.
Core question:
What would we change if we built this ourselves?
Why this matters:
This prevents “clone content” and makes you feel like a creative builder.
Example titles:
We Rebuilt This Viral AI Tool — But Made It Better
This Product Was Brilliant, But We Fixed Its Biggest Flaw
Pillar 5: Build Under Constraint
Format: Add a rule to make it a game.
Constraint ideas:
only Claude Code
only open-source tools
90-minute limit
under $20
no frontend libraries
one-shot prompt only
can’t manually code certain parts
Why this matters:
Constraint creates tension, retention, and identity.
Example titles:
We Had 90 Minutes to Rebuild This AI Product
Could Claude Code Recreate This Viral Tool in One Session?
Pillar 6: Open-Source Equivalent
Format: Take a polished commercial idea and build the lean open version.
Core question:
What’s the simplest useful version anyone can build?
Why this matters:
This is practical, empowering, and community-friendly.
Example titles:
We Built an Open Version of This Popular AI Product
Here’s the Lean Version of a Viral AI Startup
Pillar 7: Lessons From the Build
Format: Meta-analysis from multiple rebuilds.
Core question:
What patterns keep showing up in winning AI products?
Why this matters:
This turns one-off content into long-term authority.
Example topics:
What 10 Viral AI Products Had in Common
The UX Patterns Behind the Best AI Demos
What Rebuilding 12 AI Products Taught Us
Recommended pillar mix
For your first 12 pieces:
5 Viral Rebuilds
2 Hype Audits
2 Feature Extractions
2 Better Than the Original
1 Lessons From the Build
That mix keeps the format fresh while preserving a clear identity.

3) Virality scoring mechanism
This is different from hook scoring.
A hook can be good for building. A piece can still fail as content.
Virality scoring tells you whether the story packaging is strong enough.
Score each from 1 to 5.
A. Instant curiosity
Would the title alone trigger:
“Wait, what?”
Examples:
We Rebuilt Today’s #1 Product Hunt Launch
This AI Demo Went Viral. So We Tried to Clone the Core Idea
Could Claude Code Recreate This in 90 Minutes?
B. Stakes
Is there a clear consequence or tension?
Examples of stakes:
time limit
quality target
blind comparison
must match a feature
must launch same day
constrained toolset
Low virality often comes from low stakes.
C. Novelty
Does it feel fresh, not like generic AI content?
Examples of low-novelty packaging:
“Claude Code tutorial”
“How to use AI agents”
“Build an app with AI”
Examples of high-novelty packaging:
“We rebuilt a viral product”
“We tested whether the hype was fake”
“We isolated the feature that made this blow up”
D. Visual promise
Can the thumbnail / hero image tell a story fast?
Good visual ingredients:
original product vs your version
countdown timer
progress board
before/after
dramatic feature comparison
“viral object” on left, your build on right
E. Emotional engine
What emotion drives the piece?
Best emotions for your format:
curiosity
challenge tension
surprise
competence aspiration
skepticism
delight
If a piece is purely informative, virality drops.
F. Shareability
Would someone send this to:
a founder,
a builder friend,
a colleague,
an AI enthusiast?
High-share reasons:
“You should see how simple this actually was”
“This breakdown explains why this product spread”
“This is how you’d build it”
G. Identity pull
Does watching this make the viewer feel like:
an insider,
a smart builder,
an early adopter,
someone who understands what’s actually happening?
Identity is huge. People share things that reinforce how they see themselves.
H. Clipability
Can you extract 3–5 short moments?
Examples:
“We found the real trick”
“The hardest part had nothing to do with AI”
“This took 4 prompts to crack”
“This one feature made the whole product work”
If a piece has no clip-worthy moments, it’s harder to grow distribution.
Final virality score
Use this formula:
Virality Score =
Instant curiosity × 2
Stakes × 1.5
Novelty × 2
Visual promise × 1.5
Emotional engine × 1.5
Shareability × 1.5
Identity pull × 1.5
Clipability × 1
Max score = 57.5
Decision rule
46+ = high viral potential
38–45 = strong
30–37 = decent, but improve packaging
below 30 = weak packaging even if the build is good
Important rule
If Hook Score is high but Virality Score is low, do not drop the idea.
Instead, repackage it:
add a time constraint
narrow to one killer feature
add a blind test
frame it as myth-busting
compare your version against the original

