5) Newsletter template
The newsletter should feel like a premium field report, not a blog post.
It should be:
fast to scan,
story-driven,
visual,
and easy to repurpose into video.
Newsletter structure
1. Subject line
Use one of these patterns:
We Rebuilt Today’s #1 Product Hunt Launch
This AI Demo Went Viral. Here’s How We’d Build It
We Tried to Recreate a Trending GitHub Project
The Real Trick Behind This Viral AI Product
Can Claude Code Rebuild This?
Goal:
Make the subject line sound like a mission, not a newsletter.

2. Opening hook
3–5 lines max.
Template:
what happened,
why it got attention,
what challenge you’re taking on.
Example:
Today’s hook: a product that just broke out on Product Hunt because it made X feel insanely easy.
The question isn’t whether it’s cool.
The question is: can we recreate the core experience ourselves fast enough to understand what actually made it work?

3. The object of the week
A compact profile card.
Include:
name
source of discovery
why it’s trending
one-line value proposition
public signal snapshot
Images/artifacts to add
hero screenshot of the product/demo/repo
source badge image: Product Hunt, GitHub Trending, Show HN, X, etc.
signal snapshot card with stars/upvotes/engagement markers
optional tweet screenshot if the social proof matters
This section should visually answer:
Why are we paying attention to this at all?

4. Why it worked
This is a short teardown.
Use 3 mini-subsections:
What users saw
What made it feel magical
What probably drove the virality
Images/artifacts to add
annotated screenshot with arrows/callouts
“magic breakdown” diagram
side-by-side of product surface vs inferred backend logic
This is where your analytical voice starts shining.

5. The rebuild brief
This section makes the issue feel like a challenge.
Include:
objective
constraints
tool stack
what counts as success
what you are deliberately ignoring
Template:
Goal: recreate the core user experience, not the full production product.
Constraint: only use Claude Code + standard APIs + 90 minutes.
Success = if a new user feels the same “aha” moment in our version.
Images/artifacts to add
challenge card
timer graphic
feature checklist
“scope line” graphic showing what’s in/out

6. How we think it works
This is the reverse-engineering layer.
Break into:
probable inputs
model / workflow
orchestration
UX layer
hidden complexity
Images/artifacts to add
simple architecture diagram
flowchart
block diagram
“core loop” illustration
Keep this visually clean. One page / one image should make the logic obvious.

7. The build log
This is the heart of the issue.
Use a progression format:
Attempt 1
What broke
What changed
Attempt 2
What finally worked
This section should feel alive, not polished to death.
Images/artifacts to add
screenshots of iterations
before/after comparisons
code snippet screenshots only if visually useful
short GIFs or linked clips
debugging snapshots
“decision cards” with key pivots
Important:
Don’t add too much raw code in the newsletter. Show code only when it teaches a specific decision.

8. Final comparison
This is where tension resolves.
Compare:
original product
your rebuilt version
what matched
what didn’t
what was harder than expected
what turned out to be easier than expected
Images/artifacts to add
side-by-side product comparison
feature matrix
scorecard
blind test panel if possible
This section is critical for satisfaction.

9. The real lesson
This is the transfer layer.
Use a format like:
Lesson 1: the wow factor was actually ___
Lesson 2: the hardest part was ___
Lesson 3: if you were building this from scratch, start with ___
This is where readers walk away smarter.
Images/artifacts to add
distilled framework card
reusable checklist
